Name: John Doe
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, Type 2 Diabetes, Hyperlipidemia

John Doe presented to the emergency department with a fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reported feeling ill for the past week and had not sought medical attention until his symptoms worsened. Upon examination, he was found to have a temperature of 101.7°F, a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute, and an oxygen saturation of 88% on room air. A chest x-ray revealed bilateral infiltrates consistent with COVID-19.

John's past medical history revealed hypertension, Type 2 Diabetes, and hyperlipidemia. He reported no known allergies and had not traveled outside of the country in the past year. John's family history was unremarkable.

John was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen therapy and intravenous fluids. He was also started on remdesivir and dexamethasone per hospital protocol for COVID-19 treatment. Name: John Smith
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Sales Manager
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia

Case Presentation:

John Smith is a 45-year-old male who was diagnosed with COVID-19. He presented to the emergency department with a 4-day history of fever, cough, shortness of breath, and body aches. He reported no recent travel history or exposure to anyone with COVID-19. John has a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidemia and takes lisinopril and atorvastatin daily.

On examination, John appeared ill and was found to have a temperature of 101.5°F, a respiratory rate of 24 breaths per minute, and an oxygen saturation of 89% on room air. Lung auscultation revealed crackles in the lower lung fields bilaterally. A chest X-ray showed bilateral infiltrates consistent with pneumonia.

John was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen, remdesivir, and dexamethasone. His blood work showed an elevated C-reactive protein level and a mild lymphopenia. His hypertension and hyperlipidemia were managed with his usual medications.

Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, hyperlipidemia, asthma, and type 2 diabetes

John Doe presented to the emergency department with a history of fever, cough, and shortness of breath for the past five days. He had a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, asthma, and type 2 diabetes. He had no recent travel history or exposure to anyone with COVID-19. John's vital signs on presentation showed a temperature of 101.2°F, heart rate of 102 beats per minute, respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation of 88% on room air. A chest X-ray showed bilateral infiltrates consistent with viral pneumonia.

John was diagnosed with COVID-19 and admitted to the hospital for further management. He was started on supplemental oxygen and intravenous fluids. His medications were adjusted to ensure adequate control of his hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and diabetes. He received remdesivir and dexamethasone as per hospital protocol for COVID-19 treatment.
